Green is the [color](/Color) that resides between [cyan](/Cyan) and [yellow](/Yellow) on the [visible spectrum](/Visible_spectrum). It is perceived when light possesses a [dominant wavelength](/Dominant_wavelength) of approximately 495–570 [nm](/Nanometre). In [subtractive color](/Subtractive_color) systems, prevalent in painting and color printing, green is achieved by blending yellow and cyan. Conversely, within the [RGB color model](/RGB_color_model), which governs televisions and computer displays, green stands as one of the [additive primary colors](/Additive_primary_colors), alongside red and blue. These primary colors are mixed in various proportions to generate the entire spectrum of colors. The most significant natural source of green is [chlorophyll](/Chlorophyll), the vital chemical compound that enables plants to perform [photosynthesis](/Photosynthesis), converting sunlight into chemical energy. Many organisms have evolved to adopt a green coloration, serving as [camouflage](/Camouflage) within their verdant surroundings. Furthermore, numerous [minerals](/Mineral) exhibit a green hue, most famously the [emerald](/Emerald), whose distinctive color is attributed to its [chromium](/Chromium) content.

During the [post-classical](/Post-classical_history) and [early modern](/Early_modern_period) periods in Europe, green was the color that signified wealth, commerce, and the burgeoning merchant and banking classes, distinguishing them from the nobility who exclusively wore red. This historical association persists in certain contexts; for instance, the benches in the British [House of Commons](/House_of_Commons), representing the commoners, are green, while those in the [House of Lords](/House_of_Lords), representing the aristocracy, are red. Green also holds a long-standing historical connection with [Ireland](/Ireland) and [Gaelic culture](/Gaelic_culture). It is revered as the historic color of [Islam](/Islam), symbolizing the lush and abundant vegetation of [Paradise](/Paradise). Historically, it was the color of the banner carried by [Muhammad](/Muhammad), and it continues to be prominently featured in the flags of nearly all Islamic nations.

Surveys conducted across [American](/Americas), European, and [Islamic countries](/Muslim_world) consistently reveal that green is the color most frequently linked with [nature](/Nature), [life](/Life), [health](/Health), [youth](/Youth), [spring](/Spring_(season)), [hope](/Hope), and [envy](/Envy). Interestingly, within the [European Union](/European_Union) and the [United States](/United_States), green can occasionally carry connotations of [toxicity](/Toxicity) or poor health. However, in China and most of Asia, its associations are overwhelmingly positive, representing fertility and happiness. Its strong connection to nature has also made it the de facto color of the [environmental movement](/Environmental_movement). Political entities advocating for environmental protection and social justice often self-identify as part of the [Green movement](/Green_politics), frequently adopting the name "Green parties." This has permeated advertising, with companies increasingly promoting green or [environmentally friendly](/Environmentally_friendly) products. Green also traditionally signifies safety and permission, as exemplified by a green traffic light indicating it is safe to proceed, or a [green card](/Green_card) granting permanent residency in the United States.

Etymology and linguistic definitions

The word "green" shares its Germanic roots with words meaning "grass" and "grow."

The word "green" originates from the [Middle English](/Middle_English) and [Old English](/Old_English) word "grene." Similar to the [German](/German_language) word "grün," it shares the same root as the words for "grass" and "grow." This etymological lineage traces back to a [Common Germanic](/Common_Germanic) root, *gronja-, which is also evident in [Old Norse](/Old_Norse) "grænn" and [Old High German](/Old_High_German) "gruoni" (though not attested in [East Germanic](/East_Germanic_languages)). Ultimately, it derives from a [PIE root](/PIE_root) *ghre- meaning "to grow," and is semantically related to "grass" and "to grow."
The earliest recorded instance of the word "green" being used as a color term in Old English dates back to approximately AD 700.

The [Latin](/Latin) word "viridis" also provides a genuine and widely used term for "green." This word is related to "virere" ("to grow") and "ver" ("spring"), and it gave rise to terms in several [Romance languages](/Romance_languages), such as French "vert" and Italian "verde" (and English words like "vert" and "verdure"). Similarly, the [Slavic languages](/Slavic_languages) have the term "zelenъ." [Ancient Greek](/Ancient_Greek) possessed a term for a yellowish, pale green – "chloros" (related to the color of chlorine), which is cognate with "khloeros" ("verdant") and "khloē" ("[chloe](/Chloe), the green of new growth").

Consequently, the aforementioned language families (Germanic, Romance, Slavic, Greek) all possess ancient terms for "green" that are derived from words signifying fresh, sprouting vegetation.
However, [comparative linguistics](/Comparative_linguistics) clearly indicates that these terms were independently coined over the past few millennia, and there is no identifiable single [Proto-Indo-European](/Proto-Indo-European_language) origin or word for "green." For instance, the Slavic "zelenъ" is cognate with [Sanskrit](/Sanskrit) "harithah" (meaning "yellow, ochre, golden").
The [Turkic languages](/Turkic_languages) also feature the word "jašɨl," meaning "green" or "yellowish green," which can be compared to a Mongolian word for "meadow."

Languages where green and blue are considered the same color

• Main article: [Blue–green distinction in language](/Blue%E2%80%93green_distinction_in_language)

The concept of "green" in contemporary European languages typically encompasses wavelengths from approximately 520 to 570 nm. However, many historical and non-European languages categorize colors differently, sometimes using a single term for the range of approximately 450–530 nm (covering both blue and green) and another for approximately 530–590 nm (covering green and yellow).

In certain languages, including classical [Chinese](/Chinese_language), [Thai](/Thai_language), archaic [Japanese](/Japanese_language), and [Vietnamese](/Vietnamese_language), the same word can denote either blue or green. The [Chinese character](/Chinese_character) 青 (pronounced "qīng" in [Mandarin](/Standard_Mandarin), "ao" in Japanese, and "thanh" in [Sino-Vietnamese](/Sino-Vietnamese_vocabulary)) has a meaning that spans both blue and green; traditionally, blue and green are considered shades of "青." More modern terms distinguish them as 藍 (lán in Mandarin) and 綠 (lǜ in Mandarin), respectively. Japanese also possesses two specific terms for green: 緑 (midori), derived from the classical Japanese descriptive verb "midoru" (meaning "to be in leaf, to flourish," referring to trees), and グリーン (guriin), borrowed from the English word "green." Nevertheless, in Japan, while traffic lights use the same colors as elsewhere, the green light is conventionally referred to using the same word as blue, "aoi," because green is traditionally viewed as a shade of "aoi." Similarly, green variants of certain fruits and vegetables, such as green apples or green [shiso](/Perilla) (as opposed to red apples and red shiso), will be described with the word "aoi." Vietnamese employs a single word for both blue and green, "xanh," with variations like "xanh da trời" (azure, literally "sky blue"), "lam" (blue), and "lục" (green; also "xanh lá cây," literally "leaf green").

The term "green" in modern European languages typically corresponds to wavelengths between 520 and 570 nm. However, numerous historical and non-European languages define this range differently, often employing a term for the blue-green spectrum (around 450–530 nm) and another for the green-yellow spectrum (around 530–590 nm). In the comparative study of [color terms](/Color_term) across global languages, "green" as a distinct category is found primarily in languages that possess a fully developed range of six basic colors (white, black, red, green, yellow, and blue), or less commonly in systems with five colors (white, red, yellow, green, and black/blue). These languages have introduced supplementary vocabulary for "green," but these terms are often recognizable as recent borrowings that were not originally color descriptors, much like the English adjective "orange," which was initially the name of a fruit. For example, the [Thai](/Thai_language) word "kheīyw," besides meaning "green," also carries connotations of "rank" and "smelly," along with other unpleasant associations.

The [Celtic languages](/Celtic_languages) historically used a term for "blue/green/grey," Proto-Celtic *glasto-, which gave rise to Old Irish "glas" (meaning "green, grey") and Welsh "glas" (meaning "blue"). This word shares a cognate with the Ancient Greek "glaukos" ("bluish green"), contrasting with "khloros" ("yellowish green") mentioned earlier.

A dark green rectangle

In contemporary Japanese, the term for green is 緑 (midori), while the older term for "blue/green," 青 (ao), now specifically means "blue." However, in certain contexts, green is still conventionally referred to as 青, as seen in "blue traffic light" (青信号, ao shingō) and "blue leaves" (青葉, aoba), reflecting the absence of a clear blue-green distinction in older Japanese. More accurately, traditional Japanese color terminology grouped certain shades of green with blue, and others with yellow tones.

