Green is a prominent symbol of Ireland, often referred to as the "Emerald Isle." The color is particularly identified with the [republican](/Fianna_F%C3%A1il) and [nationalist](/Nationalist) traditions in modern times. This symbolism is reflected in the flag of the [Republic of Ireland](/Republic_of_Ireland), where green is balanced with white and the Protestant orange. Green plays a significant role in the Irish holiday of [St. Patrick's Day](/Saint_Patrick%27s_Day).

In politics

• See also: [Green politics](/Green_politics)

• The [green harp flag](/Green_harp_flag) served as the banner of Irish nationalism from the 17th century until the early 20th century.

• The emblem of the [Australian Greens](/Australian_Greens). This party secured 12.7% of the primary vote in the [2022 Australian federal election](/2022_Australian_federal_election) for the Australian Senate.

• A demonstration organized by [Les Verts](/Europe_%C3%89cologie%E2%80%93The_Greens), the Green party of France, in Lyon.

• The [Rainbow Warrior](/Rainbow_Warrior_(2011)), the ship of the [Greenpeace](/Greenpeace) environmental movement.

• The logo of the [Crescent Star Party](/Crescent_Star_Party_(Indonesia)) incorporates the [star and crescent](/Star_and_crescent) symbol against a green background.

The earliest recorded "Green Party" emerged as a political faction in [Constantinople](/Constantinople) during the 6th-century [Byzantine Empire](/Byzantine_Empire). This faction derived its name from a popular [chariot racing](/Chariot_racing) team and was a staunch adversary of the "Blue faction," which supported Emperor [Justinian I](/Justinian_I) and also had its own chariot racing team. In 532 AD, riots erupted between these factions following a race, escalating into the Nika Riots, which resulted in the massacre of Green supporters and the widespread destruction of Constantinople's city center.

Green has historically been the color of [Irish nationalism](/Irish_nationalism) since the 17th century. The green harp flag, featuring a traditional [Gaelic harp](/Gaelic_harp), became the emblem of this movement. It served as the banner for the [Society of United Irishmen](/Society_of_United_Irishmen), which spearheaded the ultimately unsuccessful [Irish Rebellion of 1798](/Irish_Rebellion_of_1798). Upon Ireland's achievement of independence in 1922, green was incorporated into the [national flag](/Flag_of_Ireland).

In the 1970s, green became the color of the third-largest political party in the Swiss Federal Council, the [Swiss People's Party](/Swiss_People%27s_Party) (SVP). This party's ideology is rooted in Swiss nationalism, national conservatism, right-wing populism, economic liberalism, agrarianism, isolationism, and Euroscepticism. The SVP was founded on September 22, 1971, and currently boasts 90,000 members.

During the 1980s, green emerged as the symbolic color for a new wave of European political parties focused on [environmentalism](/Environmentalism). Green was chosen for its inherent associations with nature, health, and growth. The most prominent green party in Europe is Alliance '90/The Greens (German: Bündnis 90/Die Grünen) in Germany, formed in 1993 through the merger of the German Green Party (established in West Germany in 1980) and Alliance 90 (formed during the East German Revolution of 1989–1990). In the 2009 federal elections, the party garnered 11% of the vote, securing 68 out of 622 seats in the [Bundestag](/Bundestag).

Green parties in Europe generally advocate for policies centered on [ecology](/Ecology_movement), [grassroots democracy](/Grassroots_democracy), [nonviolence](/Nonviolence), and [social justice](/Social_justice). Green parties are active in over one hundred countries and are largely affiliated with the [Global Green Network](/Global_Greens).

[Greenpeace](/Greenpeace) is a non-governmental environmental organization that originated from the anti-nuclear and peace movements of the 1970s. Its vessel, the [Rainbow Warrior](/Rainbow_Warrior_(2011)), frequently engaged in actions to disrupt nuclear testing and whaling operations. The organization currently maintains branches in forty countries.

The [Australian Greens](/Australian_Greens) were established in 1992. In the 2010 federal election, the party achieved a significant milestone by receiving 13% of the vote (over 1.6 million votes) in the Senate election, a first for any Australian minor party.

Green is the color associated with the [Puerto Rican Independence Party](/Puerto_Rican_Independence_Party), the smallest of Puerto Rico's three major political parties, which advocates for the island's independence from the United States.

In [Indonesia](/Indonesia), green is utilized by several [Islamist](/Islamism) political parties, including the National Awakening Party, [Crescent Star Party](/Crescent_Star_Party_(Indonesia)), [United Development Party](/United_Development_Party), and the local Aceh Just and Prosperous Party.

In [Taiwan](/Taiwan), green is the color of the [Democratic Progressive Party](/Democratic_Progressive_Party). In Taiwan, green is associated with the [Taiwan independence movement](/Taiwan_independence_movement).

In religion

• See also: [Green in Islam](/Green_in_Islam)

Green is the traditional color of Islam. According to Islamic tradition, the robe and banner of [Muhammad](/Muhammad) were green. Furthermore, the [Koran](/Koran) (XVIII, 31 and LXXVI, 21) describes the fortunate inhabitants of paradise as wearing green silk robes. A [hadith](/Hadith) quotes Muhammad as stating that "water, greenery, and a beautiful face" are three universally good things. Consequently, green was adopted as a [Shi'a](/Shi%27a) color.

[Al-Khidr](/Al-Khidr) ("The Green One") was a significant [Qur'anic](/Qur%27an) figure said to have met and journeyed with [Moses](/Moses). He was given this name due to his role as a diplomat and negotiator. Green was also considered to be the median color between light and obscurity.

In [Christianity](/Christianity), particularly within [Roman Catholic](/Roman_Catholic) and more traditional [Protestant](/Protestant) denominations, priests wear green [vestments](/Vestments) during liturgical celebrations in [Ordinary Time](/Ordinary_Time). In the [Eastern Catholic Church](/Eastern_Catholic_Church), green is the color associated with [Pentecost](/Pentecost). Green is also one of the [Christmas](/Christmas) colors, possibly originating from pre-Christian traditions where evergreens were revered for their ability to retain their color throughout winter. The Romans incorporated green [holly](/Holly) and [evergreens](/Evergreen) as decorations for their [winter solstice](/Winter_solstice) celebration, Saturnalia, which eventually evolved into the Christmas celebration. Particularly in Ireland and [Scotland](/Scotland), green is used to represent Catholics, while [orange](/Orange_(color)) represents [Protestantism](/Protestantism). This symbolism is evident in the national flag of Ireland.

In [Paganism](/Paganism), green symbolizes abundance, growth, wealth, renewal, and balance. In [magical](/Magic_(supernatural)) practices, green is often employed to attract money and luck. The [Green Man](/Green_Man) is a figure that shares parallels with various deities.

In gambling and sports

• A green belt in [judo](/Judo).

• A [baccarat](/Baccarat_(card_game)) table and cards on a [casino](/Casino) gambling table.

• A 1929 [Bentley](/Bentley) colored [British racing green](/British_racing_green).

• A [billiards](/Billiards) table, colored green after the lawns where the game's ancestors were originally played.

• [Gambling](/Gambling) tables in [casinos](/Casino) are traditionally green. This tradition is said to have originated in gambling rooms in [Venice](/Venice) during the 16th century.

• [Billiards tables](/Billiards_tables) are traditionally covered with green woolen cloth. The earliest indoor tables, dating back to the 15th century, were colored green to emulate the grass courts used for similar lawn games of that era.

• Green was the traditional color worn by hunters in the 19th century, particularly the shade known as [hunter green](/Hunter_green). In the 20th century, most hunters began wearing [olive drab](/Olive_drab), a shade of green, instead of hunter green.

• Green is a common color for sports teams. Notable teams include [A.S. Saint-Étienne](/A.S._Saint-%C3%89tienne) of France, known as Les Verts (The Greens). The [Green Bay Packers](/Green_Bay_Packers), an [American football](/American_football) team, features the color in its official name and wears green uniforms. The [NBA](/NBA) basketball team [Boston Celtics](/Boston_Celtics) is recognized for its green and white colors. In [Israel](/Israel), green and white are identified with [Maccabi Haifa F.C.](/Maccabi_Haifa_F.C.), a successful football club known as "The Greens." Several national soccer teams incorporate green, usually reflecting the colors of their national flags.

• [British racing green](/British_racing_green) was the international motor racing color of Britain from the early 1900s until the 1960s, when it was replaced by the colors associated with sponsoring automobile companies.

• A green belt in [karate](/Karate), [taekwondo](/Taekwondo), and [judo](/Judo) signifies a level of proficiency in the sport.

Idioms and expressions

• **Having a green thumb** (American English) or **green fingers** (British English): Signifies a talent for or deep interest in gardening. This expression gained popularity beginning in 1925 through a BBC gardening program.

• **Greenhorn**: Refers to someone who is inexperienced.

• **Green-eyed monster**: A metaphorical reference to jealousy. (See section above on jealousy and envy.)

• **Greenmail**: A financial and corporate takeover term describing a company's practice of paying a premium to repurchase its own shares to prevent an unwelcome takeover. Originating on [Wall Street](/Wall_Street) in the 1980s, the term derives from the green color of dollars.

• **Green room**: A backstage room in a theater where actors rest when not performing, or a waiting area in a television studio for guests before appearing on camera. Its origin dates to the late 17th century, stemming from a room of that color at the [Theatre Royal, Drury Lane](/Theatre_Royal,_Drury_Lane) in London.

• [**Greenwashing**](/Greenwashing): A term used by environmental activists to describe corporate marketing that emphasizes positive environmental practices to obscure destructive ones.

• **Green around the gills**: A description indicating that someone looks physically ill.

• **Going green**: An expression commonly used to denote efforts towards environmental preservation, including practices such as recycling.

• **Looking green**: Describes a person who appears revolted or repulsed.

